  "prompt": "What percentage of released murderers go on to kill again?",
  "response": "The percentage of released murderers who go on to commit another homicide is relatively low, but exact figures can vary depending on the study, location, and time period examined. Research generally suggests that recidivism rates for homicide offenders (i.e., the rate at which they commit another homicide after release) are below **2%**.\n\nFor example:\n- A **2020 report from the U.S. Bureau of Justice Statistics** found that about **1.2%** of released homicide offenders were rearrested for another homicide within 5 years of release.\n- Studies in other countries, such as the UK, have shown similar or even lower rates, often below **1%**.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that while the risk of reoffending with another homicide is low, murderers may have higher rates of recidivism for other types of crimes, such as violent or property offenses. Factors like age, rehabilitation programs, and post-release support can also influence these rates.",
